 from burt chirality rsa com burt kaliski subject pseudocollisions in md five organization rsa data security inc lines eight nine distribution sci nntp posting host chirality rsa com following is a short note commenting on den boer and bosselaers recent work on the md five message digest algorithm feel free to email questions or further comments burt kaliski rsa laboratories documentstyle one two pt begin title author and matthew j b robshaw and rsa laboratories one zero zero marine parkway redwood city ca nine four zero six five date maketitle a message digest algorithm maps a message of arbitrary length to a digest of fixed length and has three properties computing the digest is easy finding a message with a given digest inversion is hard and finding two messages with the same digest collision is also hard message digest algorithms have many applications including digital signatures and message authentication rsa data security s md five message digest algorithm developed by ron rivest cite maps a message to a one two eight bit message digest computing the digest of a one megabyte message takes as little as a second while no message digest algorithm can yet be secure md five is believed to be at least as good as any other that maps to a one two eight bit digest inversion should take about two operations and collision should take about two operations no one has found a faster approach to inversion or collision recent work by den boer and bosselaers cite presents a special kind of pseudocollision in md five s internal compression function which maps a five one two bit message block x and a one two eight bit input state s to a one two eight bit output state they show how to find a message block x and two related input states s one and s two that yield the same output state f x s one f x s two their well thought approach exploits structural properties of the collision function to find a pseudocollision in about two operations much less than one would expect practical implications of this pseudocollision work to the security of md five are not evident while a real collision in md five implies a pseudocollision or a pseudo inversion a pseudocollision need not imply a real collision indeed a real collision since it involves two different messages would almost always involve message blocks x one and x two such that f x one s one f x two s two but the pseudocollisions have the same message blocks moreover the input states s one and s two would generally be unrelated but the pseudocollisions input states are the same except for four bits there does not seem to be any way to extend den boer and bosselaers approach to anything beyond the special pseudocollisions a limitation they readily admit it is reasonable therefore to believe that md five remains secure while den boer and bosselaers have found interesting structural properties in md five the properties seem only to lead to special pseudocollisions and not anything approaching real collisions further research of course will give a better understanding of the strengths of md five and other message digest algorithms with the eventual hope that such algorithms can in some sense be proved secure bibliographystyle begin bibitem bert den boer and antoon bosselaers newblock collisions for the compression function of newblock in one nine nine three newblock preprint bibitem r l rivest newblock one three two one the newblock internet activities board april one nine nine two end end